{"ts":"2026-06-27T06:08:58.603Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Defining AI Operations Center**\n\nOkay, I'm starting to visualize this \"AI operations command center.\" The key seems to be internal, focusing on client agent operations, their health, and governance, as per instructions. The landing page is off-limits. I'm focusing on defining the scope and features first, before getting too specific on design or architecture. It's a bit early, but I need to make some notes for later as an aide memoire.\n\n\n**Refining Agent Operations Data**\n\nOkay, I've got the data structure for client agent operations fleshed out. I'm adding fields for owner assignment, severity, type, and client account names. The goal is to create a rich local dataset initialized with these fields. I'm focusing on the observability UI now. I'm thinking of status rails, health cards, tables, and a detail drawer. I'll need to figure out how to add the lint and build processes.\n\n\n**Adding Agent Details & Filters**\n\nNow I'm diving deeper into agent details. I am adding project links to each agent with hover states, linking to `/admin/projects`. I see projects like `proj-001` and `proj-002` are available. I'm also implementing owner assignment (Dr. Vance, Mercer, etc.) to agents and alerts. Finally, I'm integrating filters by client, project, agent type, status, severity, and owner, providing granular control and improved observability.\n\n\n**Enhancing Data Display & Simulation**\n\nI'm working on adding interactive owner assignment to the agent table using a dropdown, all within a React state array for a local simulation. To avoid confusion, I'm including a prominent notice bar. It will indicate that this is a simulated control console, named \"GFF AI Observability Sandbox Simulator.\" I'm planning a premium observability UI layout, with header badges, a status bar, and health cards. I'm focusing on demonstrating agent stats and simulated health metrics.\n\n\n**Visualizing Advanced Telemetry**\n\nI'm now integrating mini sparklines, animated indicators, and status rails to visualize agent latency and active alerts. I'm considering the main board layout with filters on top, health cards next, and the agent table below, with a side panel for governance alerts. I'm also planning the details drawer to display real-time logs, health charts, and interactive fields. I am checking the existing `ClientAiOperationsPage` for standard layout styles. I also must run lint and build to resolve any errors.\n\n\n"}}
